<div class="asset">
  <h2 style="margin-bottom:0.3rem;">Lead Intelligence: The 5-Signal Synthesis</h2>
  <div style="color:#555; font-size:0.8rem; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.1em; margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Apartment Locator &middot; lead_intelligence.py</div>

  <p>Every inbound lead gets profiled before the agent sends a single message. Not from a credit bureau. Not from a background check service. From five independent signals extracted from whatever data we have: the inquiry itself, the conversation, the renter's employer, the phone number's area code, and the ZIP code's demographics. The system builds a financial picture from fragments.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# From lead_intelligence.py — income estimation by category

JOB_INCOME_ESTIMATES: dict[str, tuple[int, int]] = {
    "section8_voucher": (15000, 30000),
    "employed_stable":  (35000, 65000),
    "professional":     (55000, 120000),
    "self_employed":    (25000, 60000),
    "disability":       (12000, 24000),
    "cash_worker":      (20000, 35000),
    "student":          (8000, 25000),
    "gig_worker":       (20000, 45000),
    "retired":          (18000, 40000),
}

# Employer extraction — regex first, Gemini fallback
_EMPLOYER_RE = [
    re.compile(r"i (?:work|am|been) (?:at|for|with)\s+(.+?)(?:\.|\n|$)", re.I),
    re.compile(r"(?:employed|working) (?:at|for|with|by)\s+(.+?)(?:\.|\n|$)", re.I),
    re.compile(r"my (?:job|employer|company) (?:is|at)\s+(.+?)(?:\.|\n|$)", re.I),
    re.compile(r"(?:i do|i drive for|i deliver for)\s+(.+?)(?:\.|\n|$)", re.I),
]
# If regex finds "Walmart" → employed_stable → ($35K, $65K)
# If regex finds "attorney at Jones Day" → professional → ($55K, $120K)
# If regex finds nothing → Gemini extracts from full chat context</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">The Affordability Calculation</h2>
  <p>The core rule: <code>max_affordable_rent = annual_income / 36</code>. That's the 33% rent-to-income ratio that every property manager uses. We allow 15% wiggle room before flagging risk. When the math doesn't work, the agent knows before the renter does.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Five-signal financial synthesis — actual function signature

def estimate_financial_capacity(
    inquiry_rent: int = 0,        # Signal 1: what they asked about
    chat_history: str = "",       # Signal 2+3: stated budget & income
    renter_profile: dict = None,  # Signal 4: income category
    phone_state: str = "",        # metadata
    inquiry_zip: str = "",        # Signal 5: ZIP demographics
) -> dict:

# The affordability gate:
max_affordable_rent = best_income_estimate / 36
affordable = effective_budget <= max_affordable_rent * 1.15

# When it fails:
risk_note = (
    f"Rent ${effective_budget:,}/mo is {rent_to_income_pct}%"
    f" of estimated income ${best_income_estimate:,}/yr"
    f" (target: ≤33%). May need cosigner or lower unit."
)</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Credit Estimation</h2>
  <p>We don't pull credit reports. We estimate. Explicit scores mentioned in chat take priority. Self-reported quality ("my credit is great" vs "I have bad credit") is next. ZIP-based inference fills the gap — lower-income ZIPs statistically correlate with lower scores. The system detects "confident asserters" — people who claim good credit with specific language patterns — and weights their self-report higher.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Credit estimation — actual signal priority

def estimate_credit(chat_history, renter_profile, financial):
    # Priority 1: Explicit score in chat ("my credit is 720")
    score_match = _CREDIT_SCORE.search(chat_lower)
    if score_match:
        credit_score = int(score_match.group(1))
        # 700+ = good, 600-699 = fair, <600 = poor

    # Priority 2: Self-reported quality
    if _CREDIT_POOR.search(chat_lower):  # "bad credit", "my credit sucks"
        credit_estimate = "poor"
    elif _CREDIT_GOOD.search(chat_lower):  # "good credit", "no issues"
        credit_estimate = "good"

    # Priority 3: ZIP demographics
    zip_income = fin.get("zip_median_income", 0)
    if zip_income < 30000 and credit_estimate == "unknown":
        credit_estimate = "likely_fair"

    # Confident asserter detection — weights self-report higher
    confident_asserter = confidence_phrases.search(chat_lower)
    # Matches: "my credit is good", "I make good money",
    #          "I got steady income", "no problems there"</pre>
