<!-- ═══════ INVENTORY MATCHING ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2 style="margin-bottom:0.3rem;">Inventory Matching: Distance, Budget, and Reasonableness</h2>
  <div style="color:#555; font-size:0.8rem; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.1em; margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Apartment Locator &middot; inventory_agent.py</div>

  <p>The matching algorithm is LLM-driven, not deterministic. We give Gemini the renter's profile, their requirements, and the inventory. The LLM ranks properties using five weighted criteria. Neighborhood proximity is 40% of the score — calculated with geodesic distance, not ZIP codes. Budget compatibility is 25%. The remaining 35% splits across specs, timeline, and special needs.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Matching criteria priority — from inventory_agent.py

MATCHING CRITERIA:
  1. NEIGHBORHOOD PROXIMITY (40%)
     → geodesic distance in miles, not ZIP
  2. BUDGET COMPATIBILITY (25%)
     → rent within client's stated range
  3. UNIT SPECIFICATIONS (20%)
     → bedrooms, bathrooms, dwelling type
  4. TIMELINE ALIGNMENT (10%)
     → move-in date vs vacancy date
  5. SPECIAL REQUIREMENTS (5%)
     → parking, pets, amenities

# Geodesic distance — actual production code
from geopy.distance import geodesic

def calculate_neighborhood_proximity(self, client_addr, property_addr):
    client_loc = self.geocoder.geocode(client_addr)
    property_loc = self.geocoder.geocode(property_addr)
    client_coords = (client_loc.latitude, client_loc.longitude)
    property_coords = (property_loc.latitude, property_loc.longitude)
    distance = geodesic(client_coords, property_coords).miles
    return distance</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">The Gap Analysis Framework</h2>
  <p>When the renter's budget doesn't match what's available, the agent doesn't say "sorry, nothing in your range." It runs gap analysis. Three tiers of response depending on how far the gap stretches.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Gap analysis — how the agent handles budget mismatches

Gap ≤ $100:
  → "That's about a coffee a day difference."
  → Frame as manageable. Push the property.

Gap $100-$300:
  → Value proposition. Show what they get for the extra.
  → "For $150 more you're in [neighborhood] with [amenity]."
  → Compare net effective rent if move-in specials apply.

Gap > $300:
  → Deep stretch. Don't push. Find alternatives.
  → Widen geographic search radius.
  → Drop bedroom count. Suggest roommate scenarios.
  → "Honest take — $2,200 in Lincoln Park for a 1BR
     is a stretch at your budget. But I can get you
     into Ravenswood for $1,700 with the same commute."

# Net effective rent calculation
# (Monthly Rent × 12 - Move-in Savings) ÷ 12
# $2000/mo with 1 month free → $1833 net effective</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Budget Floors and Reasonableness</h2>
  <p>Every market has a floor. Below it, there's nothing to show. The system knows this before the renter does.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Market budget floors — from locator CLAUDE.md

DFW (Dallas/Fort Worth):
  Studio: $950    1BR: $1,000    2BR: $1,300

Chicago:
  Studio: $1,100  1BR: $1,200    2BR: $1,500

# If someone asks for a 1BR in Chicago for $800:
# The agent doesn't search and return nothing.
# It tells them the market reality and widens the search.
# "Studio in Rogers Park might work at that budget."

# Tonality calibration per price tier:
LOW_END  → AUTHORITATIVE tone. Direct. No hedging.
MID      → PROFESSIONAL tone. Balanced. Value-oriented.
HIGH_END → CONSULTATIVE tone. Options. Positioning.</pre>
