  <p>The CSV parsers broke. They missed 0-98% of transactions depending on the bank. The fix: stop parsing CSVs. Read the actual bank statement PDFs with pdfplumber. 367 PDFs across 6 accounts. Seven years of transaction data. The real financial picture came from the balance method — opening balance plus deposits minus withdrawals — not from trying to categorize individual transactions.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# PDF-based balance method — why CSVs failed

CSV parser results (actual production test):
  Chase:     Missed 42% of transactions
  Wells:     Missed 0% (good format)
  Wintrust:  Missed 98% of transactions
  Spirit CU: No CSV export available at all

PDF method (pdfplumber):
  367 PDFs across 6 accounts
  Opening balance + deposits - withdrawals = closing balance
  Cross-verified against statement ending balances
  100% accuracy on every account

# The real numbers:
  Total deposits (7 years):    $1.66M
  Total withdrawals (7 years): $1.67M
  Lifetime position:           ~($404K-$436K) loss
  Texas AR write-off rate:     27%</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">4-Tier Payment Verification</h2>
  <p>When a payment is disputed or missing, the system searches four independent sources before concluding anything. Each tier is a different API. The horizontal truth — the consistent story across all four — is what you actually trust.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# 4-tier payment verification

Tier 1: Spirit Portal (bank transaction records)
  → Direct bank data. ACH timestamps. Check numbers.
  → "Did the money actually move?"

Tier 2: Invoice + Lease cross-reference
  → Invoice amount vs lease terms vs actual deposit.
  → "Was this the right amount for the right unit?"

Tier 3: Zoho Books (accounting system)
  → Revenue recognition. Categorization. Tax reporting.
  → "Did we record this correctly?"

Tier 4: Contextual evidence
  → Email threads. SMS conversations. CRM notes.
  → "What did we promise vs what did we deliver?"

# The horizontal truth pattern:
# When Tier 1 says $1,200, Tier 2 says $1,200,
# Tier 3 says $1,100, and Tier 4 has an email saying
# "$100 discount for late maintenance" — now you have
# the real story. No single source tells you that.

# This same pattern — cross-referencing independent APIs
# to find the consistent truth — applies to every
# analytical problem in the business:
#   Lead quality:   Twilio logs × CRM × conversation × outcome
#   Building value: Voice calls × ILS data × actual commission paid
#   Agent perf:     Messages sent × responses × conversions × revenue</pre>
